Capital BikeShare System Data Exploration Part I¶

by Clarence Beling¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing times, stations, and races of over 150,000 bike records by race, from Washington DC Metro Area of February 2019.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

# reducing repetitive code

cat_markers = [['Member', 'o'],
               ['Casual', 's']]

def count_plot(df, string, up, order_counts) :
    sb.countplot(data = df, x = string, color = sb.color_palette()[0],  order = order_counts.index)
    locs, labels = plt.xticks()
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count = order_counts[label.get_text()]
        string = '{}'.format(count)
        plt.text(loc, count+up, string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.ylabel('Count')

def heat_plot(df, string_1, string_2) :
    plt.hist2d(data = df, x = string_1, y = string_2, cmin=0.5, cmap='viridis_r')
    plt.colorbar()

What is the structure of your dataset ?¶

There are 158,130 bikes in the dataset with 10 features (race_id, duration_sec, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, bike_id and biker_type). Three variables are numerics and the others are categorical variables with the following types :

Quantitative variables :

  • duration_sec : continious.
  • start_timestamp, end_timestamp : discrete.

Qualitative variables :

  • race_id : ordinal.
  • start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, bike_id and biker_type : nominal.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset ?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are better for predicting the best bike of the tournament.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest ?¶

I expect that biker type will have the strongest effect on each bike's performance (best time) : the smaller the duration in each race. I also think that the number of races complited by a bike and the number of participants by race will have effects on its performance, though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of duration.

Note : The races have been identified in order of date and time of recording the first bike to go. So they are classified in order, beginning with the prefix 19.

Now we have a problem about the races : the original data frame is a set of records of each bike at each race in starting order in the whole tournament. What about the race number of each bike ? And the number of bikes at each race ? To answer his questions we will load and explore two datasets named capital_bike and capital_race extracted from capital_bikeshare_clean dataset.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points ? Did you need to perform any transformations ?¶

Time variables (duration_sec, duration_sum and winner_time) took on large ranges of values, so we looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with one peak per variable.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions ? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data ? If so, why did you do this ?¶

When investigating the race_id variable, a number of question showed up about the completness of data. We needed the race number of each bike and the number of bikes at each race. So we loaded and explored the two datasets capital_bike and capital_race previously extracted from capital_bikeshare_clean dataset.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset ?¶

Time variables (duration_sec, duration_sum and winner_time) had an expected positive correlation with the races variables (race_id and race_count), even before transforming the features. An approximately linear relationship was observed when time was plotted on a log scale. We observed this two things :

  • the Member biker type have the best race times ;
  • the Member biker type have completed way more races.

Moreover, the number of races is proportional to the sum of the race times and this increase as races follow each other.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest) ?¶

Two relationships were found in the association between the participants variable and the two previous ones. Two negative correlations was observed so we haven't explored them further. There was also a small interaction with type variables (biker_type and winner_type). We just observed that the Member biker type is more numerous.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest ?¶

I extended my investigation of races against time in this section, by looking at the impact of the biker type and the number of participants. At the beginning, we observed that the number of participants decreased as the races followed each other, but the time taken by the winner was unpredictable. Then, we found that the winners were mainly the Member bike type the majority. And eventually, minority Casual bike type winners began to emerge as the number of participants decreased.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features ?¶

On the line plot of the race_id and participants distribution, it see like there's a impredictable interaction effect between the value of bike_type variable but the correlation of the distribution is negative. So the independence of those two variables is certain.

Conclusions¶

To conclude, the performance (best time) are decisive in predicting which will be the best bike, but there is also that of the number of races and that of the number of participants in a race. Thus, the Member bike type majority has the best chance of winning the tournament.
